         <p>“Of course a great is now covered with ice on each side of the river, under which there is no water, and we go constantly <hi rend="italic" xml:space="preserve">getting in </hi>with impunity. The spring sun shining on the sloping icy shores makes numerous dazzling ice-blinks, still brighter, and prolonged with rectilinear sides, in the reflection. I am surprised to find the North River more frozen than the South, and we can cross it in many places.”</p>
         <p>"XVIII / 3 September 1854-12 May 1855 / NNPM MA 1302:24 / PE 9, p.222 vol. 8; Torrey JVII, p.#"</p>
